[src:aws-config/provisioning-technology] On-demand self-service is described by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) as an essential characteristic of cloud computing.
[src:aws-config/provisioning-technology] The self-service nature of cloud computing lets end users obtain and remove cloud services―including applications, the infrastructure supporting the applications, and configuration― themselves without requiring the assistance of an IT staff member.
[src:aws-config/provisioning-technology] The automatic self-servicing may target different application goals and constraints (e.g. deadlines and cost), as well as handling different application architectures (e.g., bags-of-tasks and workflows).
[src:aws-config/provisioning-technology] Cloud users can obtain cloud services through a cloud service catalog or a self-service portal.
[src:aws-config/provisioning-technology] Because business users can obtain and configure cloud services themselves, this means IT staff can be more productive and gives them more time to manage cloud infrastructures.
